text: Saw it, definitely an interesting film. Not sure it's worth the collective circle jerk of the critics. The characters for the most part were pretty flat and forgettable. I never really cared about this kid or his parents. The speeches of great drama, like the one from the teacher in the dark room or almost all the scenes with Ethan Hawke, were preachy, canned and hammy. The most memorable performance was by the drunk stepdad played by Andrew Villarreal who was by turns terrifying and hilarious. However the technique of filming in real time is a bold and new move, a great cinematic technique. I'd love to see it incorporated into more films.
author: zyxwut321

text: 'boyhood' was such a letdown. vacuous, slow, poorly acted, poorly written and sloppily made, ultimately, NOTHING landed for me. ethan hawke and patricia arquette were okay, but the two lead kids just aren't good actors and their attempts at improv were painful to watch. none of it was, particularly, sharp or profound, whether it was a striving for a written, crafted intelligence or whether they improvised to find naturalism, the final disappointment being a series of heavy handed monologues in which the characters attempt to understand life. linklater has been trotting out the same thing since 'slacker', 'dazed and confused' and 'before sunrise' to MUCH better effect. the most overrated film in years.

text: How can people hate this movie? Or call it boring? And say it's just a waste of time and slow and non progressive without a storyline. Honestly for me this movie has been like a breath of fresh air. For anyone who is into deep shit movies and the kinds that give you feels everytime you see them, if you like movies of such kinds and not the typical stereotype cliche kinds, go for BOYHOOD. The guy who has made this film is a genius, the thoughts that he has vocalised through the movie for eg the facebook and theory of cyborgs and robots haha I think that was cool! The constant of everything and how "the moment seizes us" ya know things that Mason sees and feel, how the characters build up and how the STORYLINE is simple addictive and just beautiful. I loved the mom in the movie, she's the strong headed lady who like everyone else has problems of their own kinds, we all make it through, boyhood did exactly that. It has created history and seriously it's been a different experience watching this movie. Call me a nerd, I have watched it twice and everytime I watch it again, it moves me in a different way.  I haven't really seen something as simple yet beautiful as this movie quite lately in the recent times. Our generation needs to sit back and relax and appreciate the little things in life. This film is everything that you need to experience if you're just as confused and awkward and normal like Mason (:   "You don't need the bumpers. Life doesn't give you the bumpers" - Mason's Dad.

text: I totally wasn't prepared for how beautiful this film is, I saw it when it came out in a cinema in Kilkenny Ireland, mostly empty. I had recently lost my Mum and I had not log became a dad to a beautiful daughter. After this film I went home sat in her room and cried buckets. It showed me how quick time passes, feels like only yesterday i was in my own 'Boyhood'. ..full days of out on our bikes, long summer days and lingerie sections of catalogues.  Now childhood is but a memory, Mum n Dad are gone and i get to relive it through the daughter and son, just hope theirs is as precious yet slower than my own...
